I loved this band and saw them live twice at these shows which used to start at like 2pm and go on all day. Definitely developed my love for going to live shows in those sweaty afternoons. Their sound is typical of all the music I loved at this age. I haven't listened to them easily in over a decade so this was such trip down memory lane - bittersweet nostalgia here.

Comment: I tried bein funny for this one but I sort of just. Couldn't. I was a sad 14 year old for a litany for good reasons, and it sort of bled all over my music taste. UNFORTUNATELY, at 14 I was not spreading my wings in terms of a developed music taste, so a lot of times my taste was fished out of a limited pool. At the time I thought this song was so good and sooo deep and I dreamed that I would one day grow up into being the kind of person who gets wasted after getting dumped. At 25, I don't drink.

This band is definitely memed on, but I still listen to this song and feel for little me

I do still listen to him quite a bit while writing, but this song always breaks my focus, especially that solo he hits in there

Title: Alive
Comment: You'd think an instrumental song like this from arguably the best electronic artist in history would be great to concentrate to. However, the slowly increasing tones actually build up to give you a sense of anxiety comparable to trying to merge onto a crowded highway.

Title: The Mighty Rio Grande
Comment:
You'd think this would work. All instrumental post-rock, why not?

Well, I always think that too, but then the song starts to crescendo. I think this applies to anything This Will Destroy You... but this song, especially.

The music builds, and then I start to think about that scene from Moneyball... and suddenly, I'm not writing anymore; I'm thinking about consecutive wins and recreating on-base percentage in the aggregate.

Comment:

Title: The Safety Dance

Title: Can You Hear The Music
Comment: I always think when I'm writing fiction I should have movie scores playing to set the mood and then I always end up getting distracted and influenced by them. So I'm writing something fun and laidback then the next minute this track comes on and I can't help but find my characters grappling with the enormity of the universe, their place in it, and their role in its possible destruction.

Now when I play it in hopes that it will summon that energy again, I just think about how the person who introduced me to the song and the band is now dead, which definitely ruins any concentration.

nice and long*, repetitive vocals**, superficially repetitive music.......but there's just too many subtle changes in production and composition and i can't disengage enough to do any writing

Title: Take Me Home, Country Roads - Original Version
Comment: The year is 2304, and the fictional country of New West Virginia is a prosperous farming state home to middle-class homesteaders waiting out the apocalypse. It is also home to this iconic anthem heard round the world. Featuring a memorable chorus and powerful images about the country's gentle hills and powerful mountains, this bittersweet song makes any New West Virginian homesick, reminiscing a simpler past.

Title: Like a Virgin

Title: 'Merican
Comment: This song shows pride for the country, but also recognizes that it's not perfect, and I think that's something every national anthem should do. National pride without shame leads to nationalism, and if more people could accept that things aren't so black and white, and if the bad parts were remembered and learned from as much as the good parts are celebrated, the world would be a better place.

Title: Only Anarchists Are Pretty

We believe in free love, free LSD and that plants deserve the right to vote. Our national bird is Buzz Aldrin eating a Popeyes chicken sandwich. This is our national anthem.
